<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="98" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="98">
The single species, 
<taxonomicName authority="M.Nobis, P.D.Gudkova &amp; A.Nowak (Tzvelev)" authorityName="M.Nobis, P.D.Gudkova &amp; A.Nowak (Tzvelev)" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Neotrinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Neotrinia splendens" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Neotrinia splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is native to Asia in Afghanistan, India, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, China, Mongolia, Pakistan, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, and Uzbekistan (
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, ZL" editor="Wu, Z" journalOrPublisher="Science Press and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, Beijing and St. Louis" pageId="23" pageNumber="112" pagination="188 - 212" refId="B46" refString="Wu, ZL, Phillips, SM, 2006. 7. Tribe Stipeae. In: Wu, Z, Raven, PH, Hong, DY, Eds., Flora of China, Poaceae. Science Press and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, Beijing and St. Louis: 188 - 212" title="7. Tribe Stipeae." volumeTitle="Flora of China, Poaceae." year="2006">Wu and Phillips 2006</bibRefCitation>
). In North America 
<taxonomicName genus="N." lsidName="N. splendens" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">N. splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been introduced as an ornamental (
<bibRefCitation author="Barkworth, ME" editor="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Universtiy Press, New York" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="109 - 186" refId="B3" refString="Barkworth, ME, 2007. 10. Stipeae Dumort. In: Barkworth, ME, Capels, KM, Long, S, Anderton, LK, Piep, MB, Eds., Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Oxford Universtiy Press, New York: 109 - 186" title="10. Stipeae Dumort." volumeTitle="Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1." year="2007">Barkworth 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The species occurs in cold, semi desert regions along drainages at 2100-3800 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="355 - 489" refId="B11" refString="Freitag, H, 1985. The genus Stipa (Gramineae) in Southwest and South Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 42: 355 - 489" title="The genus Stipa (Gramineae) in Southwest and South Asia." volume="42" year="1985">Freitag 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="98" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="98">
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Psammochloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Psammochloa villosa" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Psammochloa villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Trin.) Bor is sister to 
<taxonomicName authority="M.Nobis, P.D.Gudkova &amp; A.Nowak (Tzvelev)" authorityName="M.Nobis, P.D.Gudkova &amp; A.Nowak (Tzvelev)" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Neotrinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Neotrinia splendens" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Neotrinia splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in our earlier molecular phylogeny (BS = 100, PP = 1.00) and both species share the following morphological features: basal fibrous sheaths, panicles with whorled primary branches arising from the rachis, (1-) 3-5-veined glumes with hyaline margins, short, obtuse to elliptic calluses, and evenly hairy lemmas with flexuous cauducous awns that arise between the apical teeth (
<bibRefCitation author="Freitag, H" journalOrPublisher="Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh" pageId="21" pageNumber="110" pagination="355 - 489" refId="B11" refString="Freitag, H, 1985. The genus Stipa (Gramineae) in Southwest and South Asia. Notes from the Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh 42: 355 - 489" title="The genus Stipa (Gramineae) in Southwest and South Asia." volume="42" year="1985">Freitag 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, ZL" editor="Wu, Z" journalOrPublisher="Science Press and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, Beijing and St. Louis" pageId="23" pageNumber="112" pagination="188 - 212" refId="B46" refString="Wu, ZL, Phillips, SM, 2006. 7. Tribe Stipeae. In: Wu, Z, Raven, PH, Hong, DY, Eds., Flora of China, Poaceae. Science Press and Missouri Botanical Garden Press, Beijing and St. Louis: 188 - 212" title="7. Tribe Stipeae." volumeTitle="Flora of China, Poaceae." year="2006">Wu and Phillips 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Barkworth, ME" editor="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Universtiy Press, New York" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="109 - 186" refId="B3" refString="Barkworth, ME, 2007. 10. Stipeae Dumort. In: Barkworth, ME, Capels, KM, Long, S, Anderton, LK, Piep, MB, Eds., Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Oxford Universtiy Press, New York: 109 - 186" title="10. Stipeae Dumort." volumeTitle="Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1." year="2007">Barkworth 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" author="Romaschenko, K" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="22" pageNumber="111" pagination="18 - 44" refId="B26" refString="Romaschenko, K, Peterson, PM, Soreng, RJ, Garcia-Jacas, N, Futorna, O, Susanna, A, 2012. Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology. Taxon 61 (1): 18 - 44, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" title="Systematics and evolution of the needle grasses (Poaceae: Pooideae: Stipeae) based on analysis of multiple chloroplast loci, ITS, and lemma micromorphology." url="https://doi.org/10.1002/tax.611002" volume="61" year="2012">Romaschenko et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="M.Nobis, P.D.Gudkova &amp; A.Nowak (Tzvelev)" authorityName="M.Nobis, P.D.Gudkova &amp; A.Nowak (Tzvelev)" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Neotrinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Neotrinia splendens" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="splendens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Neotrinia splendens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Psammochloa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Psammochloa villosa" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Psammochloa villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having cespitose culms without rhizomes, 4-7 (-8.5) mm long spikelets, 2.5-6.5 mm long glumes, 4.2-7.2 mm long lemmas that are evenly hairy with hairs up to 1.5 mm long, linear-lanceolate lodicules (versus flabellate), and 3.5-4.5 mm long anthers. It also differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Achnatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Achnatherum" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Achnatherum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having saw-like lemma epidermal pattern.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="98">
As noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Barkworth, ME" editor="Barkworth, ME" journalOrPublisher="Oxford Universtiy Press, New York" pageId="20" pageNumber="109" pagination="109 - 186" refId="B3" refString="Barkworth, ME, 2007. 10. Stipeae Dumort. In: Barkworth, ME, Capels, KM, Long, S, Anderton, LK, Piep, MB, Eds., Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1. Oxford Universtiy Press, New York: 109 - 186" title="10. Stipeae Dumort." volumeTitle="Magnoliophyta: Commelinidae (in part): Poaceae, part 1." year="2007">Barkworth (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, the plants are rarely grazed upon, and sometimes form dense tall stands in Asia (RJS pers. obs.; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tzvelev, NN" journalOrPublisher="Novosti Sistematiki Vysshchikh Rastenii" pageId="23" pageNumber="112" refId="B39" refString="Tzvelev, NN, 1976. Zlaki SSSR [Grasses of the Soviet Union]. Nauka Publishers USSR, Leningrad." title="Zlaki SSSR [Grasses of the Soviet Union]. Nauka Publishers USSR, Leningrad." year="1976">Tzvelev 1976</bibRefCitation>
, p. 564 comment). 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Achnatherum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Achnatherum caragana" order="Poales" pageId="9" pageNumber="98" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="caragana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="98">Achnatherum caragana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Trin.) Nevski was treated as the only other 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. subsp. sect." pageId="9" pageNumber="98" rank="section" section="Neotrinia" species="caragana" subSpecies="sect.">A. sect. Neotrinia</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Tzvelev, NN" journalOrPublisher="Novosti Sistematiki Vysshchikh Rastenii" pageId="23" pageNumber="112" refId="B39" refString="Tzvelev, NN, 1976. Zlaki SSSR [Grasses of the Soviet Union]. Nauka Publishers USSR, Leningrad." title="Zlaki SSSR [Grasses of the Soviet Union]. Nauka Publishers USSR, Leningrad." year="1976">Tzvelev 1976</bibRefCitation>
), and may belong to the genus.
</paragraph>
